  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects women and people of color who feel their identities might undermine their performance. As someone who grew up in a household where my father had a master's degree and my mother only went to primary school, I've seen firsthand how expectations can shape opportunities. When I was a young woman in college, I remember feeling nervous during math exams because I'd heard stereotypes about girls not being good at math. That anxiety wasn't just about the test—it was about the fear of confirming a narrative that said I wasn't 'smart enough.' Today, as a retired woman from Washington DC, I've watched how these stereotypes persist in classrooms and labs, especially for women and minorities. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing the fundamental nature of STEM but about creating environments where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment. It means mentorship programs that build confidence, inclusive classrooms where diverse voices are celebrated, and leaders who actively challenge biased language. I've traveled the world and seen how creative problem-solving thrives in diverse teams—this is why we must tackle stereotype threat head-on. It’s not just about fixing individual cases but fostering a culture where everyone knows they belong. In my faith as a Christian, I believe in the dignity of every person, so addressing this issue aligns with my values. We must act now to ensure that future generations don't face the same barriers I did.",
